    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When you're doing high-intensity interval training (HIIT), your muscles primarily use anaerobic metabolism to generate energy, which means they don't rely on oxygen. This process produces lactic acid as a byproduct. During your sprints, your muscles are so fatigued that they can't produce enough energy through aerobic means, so they resort to this anaerobic pathway. The lactic acid accumulates in your muscles, causing the burning sensation. \n\nAfter you stop exercising, your body shifts back to aerobic metabolism, which allows it to use oxygen to break down the lactic acid. Your liver then converts the lactic acid back into glucose, which can be used as energy or stored as glycogen for future energy needs. This process is called the Cori cycle. It may take some time, but your body will eventually clear the lactic acid from your muscles.",
      "source": "target",
