    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The buildup of lactic acid in your muscles during high-intensity exercise doesn't directly disrupt how muscle fibers work. Instead, it's more of a side effect of the energy production process. However, the accumulation of lactic acid can lead to a temporary decrease in muscle performance and endurance. This is because the lactic acid can cause muscle fatigue, which may make your muscles feel weaker and less responsive during exercise.\n\nAdditionally, the buildup of lactic acid can lower the pH level in your muscles, creating an acidic environment. This acidic environment can interfere with the function of enzymes and other proteins within the muscle cells, which may further contribute to the sensation of muscle fatigue and reduced performance.\n\nOnce you stop exercising, your body works to clear the lactic acid, convert it back into energy, and restore the muscle cells to their normal functioning. However, the process of clearing lactic acid and recovering from muscle fatigue can take some time, which is why it's important to allow yourself enough rest and recovery between intense workouts.",
